          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The Ambani legacy</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">It all started with <a href="https://www.reliancegroupindia.com/about-shri-dhirubhai-ambani" target="_blank">Dhirubhai Ambani</a>, a man of humble beginnings who launched <a href="https://www.ril.com/about/our-history" target="_blank">Reliance Industries</a> in 1966, initially as a small textile company. With Dhirubhai's unique business vision and knack for networking, Reliance grew exponentially, expanding beyond textiles into diverse sectors, including petrochemicals, telecommunications, and energy. Through strategic investments and a relentless focus on vertical integration, Reliance Industries became the largest private company in India, breaking new ground in the Indian economy.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-nov-11-1.jpg" alt="The Ambani legacy" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">His unconventional approaches and risks marked Dhirubhai’s journey. One of his boldest moves was taking Reliance public in 1977, a groundbreaking step for Indian businesses of the time. Through his public offerings, Dhirubhai garnered thousands of loyal shareholders, creating a unique shareholder culture in India. By the 1980s, Reliance had diversified into petrochemicals, building a massive production facility in Patalganga, Maharashtra. This move was pivotal, allowing Reliance to become self-sufficient, thereby controlling its supply chain—a strategic advantage that set the stage for further growth.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In 2002, after Dhirubhai’s death, his sons <a href="https://www.britannica.com/money/Mukesh-Ambani" target="_blank">Mukesh</a> and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/money/Anil-Ambani" target="_blank">Anil Ambani</a> inherited the empire. However, a <a href="https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/how-mukesh-ambani-will-split-his-empire-to-avoid-his-fathers-folly/articleshow/92558888.cms?from=mdr" target="_blank">split in 2005</a> divided Reliance’s assets, with Mukesh taking control of the core petrochemicals, oil, and telecommunications businesses, while Anil received the entertainment, financial, and power sectors. Mukesh steered Reliance towards becoming a global giant, especially with his ambitious launch of <a href="https://www.jio.com/" target="_blank">Reliance Jio</a> in 2016. Jio disrupted India’s telecom industry by offering free calls and affordable data plans, rapidly acquiring millions of subscribers. By 2020, Jio had over 400 million users and brought India into the digital age, making Mukesh a key player in Indian and global markets.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Today, Reliance Industries is valued at over $200 billion and includes retail, digital services, and green energy sectors. Mukesh Ambani’s investments in clean energy aim to position Reliance as a global leader in sustainable technologies.</p>
        </mj-text>
